gomodel:SYNGO_4544  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 3C: Whole-cell patch-clamp recordings in the granule cell layer of the DG in acute hippocampal slices measured the spontaneous miniature post-synaptic currents (mEPSCs). mEPSCs occur with lower frequency at the DG of cpg15 KO mice at P7 and persists at 2 mo of age, but is less significant.\n\nFigure 3D: In the P7 DG of cpg15 KO mice, mEPSC amplitudes were also reduced; however, this deficit was no longer observed by 2 mo of age. These results suggest that during development, cpg15 KO mice have fewer and less mature functional synapses.\n\nFigure 4B: The density of asymmetric synapses on dendritic spines was measured by unbiased stereology, cpg15 KO mice had spine synapse densities in the DG that were 26% lower than wild-type controls at 2 mo of age.\n\nTaken together, CPG15 might act to stabilize nascent synapses on dendritic spines, resulting in spine and arbor stabilization and synaptic maturation.. Experimental description: To generate general cpg15-null mice, cpg15flox/+ mice were crossed to an adenovirus EIIa promoter-driven Cre transgenic line in C57BL/6 background [Jackson Laboratory, B6.FVB-TgN(EIIa-cre)C5379Lmgd] (Lakso et al. 1996). Progeny of this cross that were heterozygous for the cpg15-null allele (cpg15+/-) were intercrossed to obtain homozygous cpg15-null mice (cpg15-/-). The absence of floxed cpg15 genomic sequence, cpg15 mRNA, and CPG15 protein was confirmed by Southern blots of tail genomic DNA (Sambrook et al. 1989), Northern blots on brain RNA (Fujino et al. 2003), and Western blots, respectively" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2916-7616" ;
        dc:date           "2022-04-29" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4544" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

